      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's true that aspirin has been replaced as a common medication for fever in children by other drugs due to the risk of Reye’s syndrome. Historically, very small doses were used, but this practice is not supported by current medical guidelines. To safely reduce your child's fever and help them to sleep, I recommend giving children's medications like acetaminophen or ibuprofen as directed on the package, but it's always best to consult a healthcare provider to ensure safe and effective treatment. Three for an hour is exactly as the label says—don't take more or stay on it longer than that. And if he's comfortable, monitor his fever and symptoms, and seek medical advice if it doesn't improve. Waiting for a call back from their doctor will help ensure he is s/he receives the proper treatment. If you haven't already, you might contact their pediatrician for advice on the situation.",
