      "content": "I apologize for the confusion. I am strongly advocating for keeping caution when giving any medication to a child. Instead of multiple doses, you should administer one dose according to the pediatric dosage guidelines on the medication's package or the healthcare provider's advice.\n\nFor children and teens, the common Total Daily Dosage of Acetaminophen follows this pattern: age in years × 10-15 mg/kg; For Ibuprofen, it's age in years × 10 mg/kg.\n\nFor example, if your child weighs around 50 pounds (approximately 23 kg), they would receive:\n\nAcetaminophen: 23 kg × 10-15 mg/kg = 230 to 345 mg per dose.\n\nAdministering this as directed should provide relief without overwhelming their system.\n\nHowever, before giving any medication, please contact your healthcare provider. They can advise on the appropriate dosage based on your child's weight and health conditions, which ensures safety and reduces the risk of unexpected side effects.",
